The towns, washed by the long sweep of the Forth‚ are shielded from the blasts of Boreas by the Grampian range. With oars and sails ye skirn Neptune's realms, dreading no Scylla or Syrtis or other terror of the deep. Nor only do ye plough the main: ye dive into the bowels of the land of Fergus and fetch lire from the depths of Tartarus. By your arte the liquid sea solidilies and solid salt emergea. The Saxon need not boant of his rock- hewn salt mines: the sea supplies you with ampler store. Let Scotia praise your industries ε without you the frosts of winter would be too fierce and all her meals insipid.
